<br>
<br>
Saffryn is returning from the guild meeting in Butcherblock and decides to turn at the first left in the path instead of continuing towards the Spires.  Before her lies a different estate than the one she's seen last time she was here.  The wild berry bushes are cut back.  The trail is more defined.  What was once an overgrown tunnel of towering rhodedendrens is now trimmed back allowing sky to be seen above.  Turning the final bend she stops short to take in the changes.  A circle of willow trees outline several acres worth of land.  The largest willow sits on the bank of a lazy creek running the length of the property. In the middle of tended lawn and gardens sits a large house, three stories tall with large many-paned windows lined with heavy lead.  Half-way up the first story, the walls are made of rounded river-rock, the rest of the walls made up of heavy wood.<br>
<br>
She walks up the path, now made of the same river-rock, and reaches for the door-knocker.  It's designed of brass in the shape of two arms clasped over an old, gnarled willow tree.  <br>
<br>
Her knock is answered by a wood-elf maid who directs her into a large entry hall tiled in smooth stone.  Before her is a staircase against the left wall with a sweeping banister leading up to a gallery with doors at either end and more stairs seem to go up to the third floor at the right end of the gallery.  Doors behind the staircase on the first floor seem to be the kitchens if her sense of smell is correct, and she guesses that the door on the right leads to the dining room.  She is led through a door on the left before the stairs.<br>
<br>
The room is airy and comfortable looking, obviously a parlor to greet guests in.  She has little time to look around before Wardrym bounds into the room, &quot;Saffy, come on upstairs,&quot;  and he turns and jumps up the stairs taking two at a time.<br>
<br>
With a crooked smile, Saffryn follows him up the stairs and past the open door on the left of the gallery, which at quick glance looks to be the family's living area, and follows him as he dissapears into the far door-way.  Just as she reaches the doorway she peeks up to her right at the stairway to the third-floor, guessing there are sleeping chambers up there, and continues through the door and enters a well-shelved library.  Wardrym has dissappeared.  <br>
<br>
Suddenly Wardrym pops his head through a small door partially hidden by a large house plant, &quot;Coming?&quot; he says, and she stiffles another smile while passing a large, comfortable couch and chairs arranged around a large lit hearth, the smell of leather and books lending to a cozy atmosphere. Passing through the last door she sees a den with a large desk near a window, and a large, long table against a wall lined with bookshelves and more books.  The long table is in disaray for the most part, and she finds Wardrym standing in front of a large parchment rolled out on the left side of the table.  Joining him, she sees a map to a tower in Felwithe.<br>
<br>
&quot;Ah, I see, you've been working on our quest,&quot; she says to Wardrym.  &quot;And before we get started on that, I have to say, you've done wonders with this old hunting lodge.  Took out all the fancy, gaudy stuff, I see too.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, it was too stiff and fancy for comfort, and when were you here before?&quot; asks Ward, curiously.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh, for the longest time, breaking into this old haunt was the dare of all dares for young ones before entering into our guilds.  That is, after properly scaring the one dared with bonfires and stories of the beheaded ghouls meandering the halls, of course,&quot; she says.<br>
<br>
&quot;Of course,&quot; Wardrym says with a grin.  &quot;Now, back to the quest.  I have the routine of the guards, memorized the way to the tower,&quot; he begins as Saffryn begins studying the map.<br>
<br>
She traces two routes to the tower, &quot;you've alternative routes, good, good.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Thought you'd appreciate that, you being a ranger,&quot; says Wardrym.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh aye, many a man is lost due to a closed path.  Always have a second,&quot; she says.<br>
<br>
She traces a staircase on the map with her finger as they begin to discuss their plans for their impending quest and asks, &quot;When do we do this?&quot;<br>
<br>
Wardrym looks her in the eye with all seriousness, &quot;Tomorrow night&quot;<br>
<br>
