look like a regular Koada'Dal,&quot; looking him up and down.<br>
<br>
Wardrym shifts his princely robes, &quot;I forgot how impractical and uncomfortable they were. Heavy too.&quot; <br>
<br>
A wry smile alits on his face as they begin descending the stairs, thinking to himself how HE should be dressed the servant knowing that it is Saffryn who is the true heir to Nobleheart and that she is unknowingly the very Koada'Dal she picks upon so often. <br>
<br>
Knowing they have time, they walk the path from Willowswood to the crossroads where they can choose to go right to Butcherbloock or left towards the Spires. They continue on to the Spires that is bustling with traffic to and from the Nexus. As they pass the turn to Lesser Faydark, they continue with small talk. Wardrym has cleaned up the orchards of Willowswood and should have a good stock of fruit for Kelethin next year. Saffryn has just achieved her 14th Season and is looking forward to new spells upon reaching her 15th. <br>
<br>
Their talk lessens as tension starts building as they reach the rolling hills just before Felwithe. Soon the towering Castle stands before them. Wardrym approaches the entrance with a nod at the guards, Saffryn following in his footsteps, looking respectfully down while hiding a snear.<br>
<br>
Wardrym makes small talk with some of the merchants, avoiding the bard in front of the tavern lest he recognise Saffy. In a private patch of grass around one of the shops, Ward hands Saffryn a bottle of invisible potion and he downs his, waving his arms to initiate the effect. Saffryn can't help but be reminded of his arm-swinging when he was following her around in Freeport, and her nick-name for him then, &quot;Mr. Bramblepants.&quot;<br>
<br>
They approach the lake, but rather than taking the left path towards the fish shops and traveling on to the Caster's Conclave of Towers, Ward directs her to the wall on the right and finds the tile that is encoded. They silently wait for the guards who patrol the area to move on. He whispers to Saffryn to place her palm upon the tile which is at first cold to her touch, but then warms. Thinking the caster's enchanted tile has read her Trueshot blood, she hears a click and sees the panel of tile wall open a crack. She quickly slips in with Wardrym close behind her. <br>
<br>
The staircase before them is a tight curl, barely wide enough for them both as they climb the dusty marble steps. First Saffryn begins to appear when the effects of the potion fade, followed by Wardrym, though it matters not at this point, as long as they avoid the few windows that dot the tall thin tower. Another tall, thin window before them, they lay their backs against the curving wall opposing the window and slide across it so as to not lay shadow before the glass letting in what little light that plays with the dust motes.<br>
<br>
The tower is the tallest of Felwithe and oversees all of Greater Faydark, what of it you can see between towering tree tops of evergreens that have stood for centuries. After a long, long climb, they reach the top and sigh with relief. They have avoided each trap set in the marble steps. If all goes well, the next traps are but tests for the inquiring elf to ensure they are of the true blood and allowed to view the the Holy Tome, the Book of Law. <br>
<br>
Looking about, this room at the top of their world is a room made up of a small circle, lit brightly with full-length windows. Between each window stands a globe to light the room even in full darkness. &quot;Ah,&quot; says Saffryn, &quot;you've brought us to the Tower of the Eternal Light. An appropriate place for the Holy book written by Tunare, herself.&quot; She tries to speak with a touch of irony but is too awed by her circumstances to carry it off well. <br>
<br>
In the middle of the room on an ornate platinum pedestal is a platinum box set with emeralds. There is a star engraved upon the box. They both circle the box and see a decorated opening the size of a fist on the side.<br>
<br>
&quot;Now what?&quot; asks Saffryn<br>
<br>
&quot;I think you put your hand in it,&quot; he replies.<br>
<br>
&quot;You think? What do you mean, you think? YOU put your hand in there,&quot; she exclaims.<br>
<br>
&quot;Um, I'm not a Trueshot&quot; he answers.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, but you're the heir to Nobleheart, one of the Star Council,&quot; she says.<br>
<br>
&quot;Yes, but there's a trick to it if you are one of the five, something you have to do with your hand while it's in the box. A Trueshot doesn't have to do anything but stick their hand in the box,&quot; he lies. <br>
<br>
Frowning at him, she rolls up her sleeve, narrows her eyes, and slowly begins to put her hand in the box.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wait, right or left hand,&quot; she asks.<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't know,&quot; he replies.<br>
<br>
&quot;What do you mean you don't know,&quot; she retorts.<br>
<br>
&quot;Um, that's part of the &quot;tricks&quot; you learn when you're an heir to the Star Council. Remember, my father hasn't shared any of those secrets with me.&quot; He says.<br>
<br>
&quot;But you THINK it won't matter because my great-great-great-great auntie was the wizard that set this thing up,&quot; she says with a raised brow.<br>
<br>
Wardrym can think of no reply but to look innocent and shrug.<br>
<br>
Saffryn scowls at him and tries not to think he looks cute when he's playing stupid.<br>
<br>
With a sigh and resolve, she puts her right fist into the box. Nothing happens. They both look at each other. She opens her fist in the box. Nothing happens. She wiggles her fingers. Nothing happens. She reaches fully into the box, extending her hand to find a depression on the far side with her middle finger. <br>
<br>
Suddenly, a device that had been laying flat on the upper inside of the box slaps down encompassing her hand painfully like a vice. From the bottom of the box, a device drives a needle up into her wrist and extracts a small vial's worth of blood from her veins. The emeralds on the outside of the box glow and Saffryn discovers it is more comfortable to not resist as the clamp grows tighter when she struggles. <br>
<br>
Both of them hold their breath as they wait for the box to do something next. Seconds seem like minutes. Cracks on the floor under the dust light up and the cracks take shape and appear to be a five pointed star. And then suddenly, all the lights go out. <br>
<br>
The emeralds on the box go back to sleep. The lit cracks in the floor fade into the dust. The device in the box release Saffryn's hand. She pulls her hand from the box, examining it for damage and finds only a tinyl hole in her wrist. A click in the room against a wall makes them both turn their heads in the direction of the sound. A crack in the ceiling against the far wall opens slightly, then slowly widens further as a small portion of the ceiling descends, supporting a small staircase to the floor of the room they are standing in. <br>
<br>
With a grin, Wardrym realizes the jeweled box has decided that Saffryn is, indeed, the heir to the Star Council seat held now by Joren Nobleheart. Another thought, &quot;if Saffryn realised the truth, instead of thinking the box accepted her for that phoney story I trumped up about the Trueshot ancestor wizardress, she'd spit nails it me, great big ogre nails at that,&quot; he chuckles aloud at the thought.<br>
<br>
&quot;Oh you think this is funny, do you, I almost wet me pants!&quot; she admonishes Ward as she stalks off to the staircase.<br>
<br>
Carefully leading up the stairs and watching for more traps and finding none, she stands before a door with a smaller door inset within it at face height. &quot;Now what do I do?&quot; she asks as she turns to Wardrym who has followed her.<br>
<br>
&quot;You open the little door and put your face close to it,&quot; he answers.<br>
<br>
&quot;What, so a claw can jump out and gouge out me eyes?&quot; she says.<br>
<br>
&quot;No, no, I know exactly what this one does. Everyone one with the blood of the Council, er in your case the blood of the Trueshot,&quot; he lies, &quot;has a strange pattern to the blood vessels in the back of their eyes, a little corner where the veins make the shape of a star. &quot; he adds.<br>
<br>
&quot;You sure?&quot; she asks.<br>
<br>
&quot;Positive, go ahead,&quot; he says, trying not to admire the butt in front of his face as she is several steps above him on the small staircase.<br>
<br>
&quot;Okay, here goes,&quot; she replies and opens the small door. A beam of blue light examines her right eye and goes out as the door clicks open. With a shrug and a deep breath she pushes the door open.<br>
<br>
<br>
