<br>
&quot;Wait, let's wait here a bit till the storm passes,&quot; he says as he sits on an exposed root of a large willow, sheltered under the umbrella of its branches.<br>
<br>
&quot;Sure, Ward. Nothing like sitting next to a large tree when there's lightening,&quot; she replies sarcastically and plops down beside him. &quot;Now, maybe we can have that talk. What are we going to do about what we found out?&quot; She pulls the hair out of her mouth that has whipped there by the rising wind as the storm continues.<br>
<br>
&quot;I've thought myself in circles about this. If we go to the Barons, they'll demand to see the original Tome and by the time they get to see it, another false one will be created to take it's place. If we go to the Princes, it will be hushed up and we'll suddenly disappear,&quot; he says loudly to be heard over the claps of thunder.<br>
<br>
Another round of thunder as the lightening casts strange images against the branches and on the nearby creek. The waters begin to churn, wild and muddy with a strong current as the skies blacken and hide the approaching dawn.<br>
<br>
&quot;What if we tell them that if anything happens to us, then what we know has been written down and will be revealed,&quot; she asks as she is whipped in the face with willow branches in the rising wind and stands to untangle herself.<br>
<br>
&quot;Thought of that, and that puts our families in danger. I think we need to find a way to get the Barons and the Princes all in one room and tell them what we know all at once, but first, there's one more secret I have to tell you,&quot; he says as he stands with a worried look, seemingly oblivious to the raging storm.<br>
<br>
Walking closer to the side of the creek and ignoring the torrent of rain as wood-elves are known to do, he turns with an unheard sigh, &quot;Saffryn, there's something you have to know, something I haven't told you. I haven't exactly lied to you, I just didn't have the right time to reveal this,&quot; he nearly has to shout.<br>
<br>
Looking suspiciously at him she turns with her hands on her hips and shouts back, &quot;Go on.&quot;<br>
<br>
He looks to the mud at his feet, and then up to her eyes, &quot;Saffryn, you aren't really a Trueshot, and I'm not really the heir of Nobleheart. In fact, YOU are the heir of Prince Joren,&quot; he shouts.<br>
<br>
First she cracks a smile, and then throwing her head back, she laughs, letting the rain fall full on her now drenched face. &quot;Oh Ward, you had me going there, you goof. Now really, how are we going to get the Barons and Princes together.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;I'm not joking Saff, it's true. You were delivered by a mid-wife named Miaza the same night I was delivered. She switched us. She gave you to the Trueshot family and gave me to the woman I have called mother all these years. Ask your mother who the mid-wife was,&quot; he says.<br>
<br>
&quot;And why would she do such a thing, why would anyone do such a thing,&quot; she asks as she squints at him through the rain, trying to figure what he's up to.<br>
<br>
&quot;There is a history of stillbirths and infant deaths before me. Prince Joren had tried for years to gain an heir through several wives. Miaza feared for my, your mother's death if she did not produce a healthy heir. They were all born sickly girls. The woman who raised you had a history of healthy boys. They were both due to deliver close to each other. When Niola Impholder-Nobleheart began her labor pains, the midwife started your, my mother's labor with the slipping of belladonna into her tea. They delivered the same night. She switched us before showing us to our mothers,&quot; he explains. <br>
<br>
Turning with Saffryn as she circles him in the mud while he continues explaining to her, &quot;She was sure you'd be another sickly girl like all the girls before you and since the Trueshot already had plenty of kids that one loss would be easier on them than on Lady Niola and took the healthy boy baby, me, to the Noblehearts. You were born here, at Willowswood, at the hunting lodge. She hid you and took you to the Trueshot's home and switched us when I was born and handed you to the Baroness Trueshot. Saffryn, you are the heir to Nobleheart. Think about it. It's how we were able to get into the chambers of the Book Of Laws.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You said it was because my ancestress set the traps, that she was a wizardress,&quot; she says.<br>
<br>
&quot;I lied.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;How do I know you aren't lying now? How do I know what is a lie and what is a truth with you,&quot; she angrily shouts at him, her fists doubled up at her sides.<br>
<br>
&quot;It's true Saffy, ask your mother who the midwife was, ask her about the storm the night you were born. It hid your cries as we were switched at birth. The device that read the blood vessels in your eye saw the star there and let you in the Tome's chamber. The box in the chamber before that read your blood to find it true. You are the high-elven heir of Nobleheart&quot; He says.<br>
<br>
&quot;I don't believe you,&quot; she shouts at him as she swings her fist around and clobbers him on his left eye. Suddenly off-balance, Ward begins to slip into the mud as she slams her left fist under his jaw. Instead of falling to his right, his weight is suddenly shifted backwards and he falls solidly in the mud, his boots catching Saffryn's ankles on the way down and flipping her suddenly on her butt.<br>
<br>
Quickly he turns over to his hands and knees and shoots his arm out to Saffryn and grabs her by the arm. She tries to kick him and he rolls over, taking her with him deeper into the mud. Sitting on top of him she twists one of her arms free and slams a muddy fist into his chest, flinging mud into her eyes and into his mouth as he stammers to calm her down. He begins to choke as he swallows more mud and starts to chuckle as he wrestles with the muddy hell-cat. Gaining an upright position he succeeds in flipping her onto his lap and slaps his muddy hand across her butt with a sound splatt, flinging more mud everywhere and chuckling louder at succeeding at getting a loud squeel out of her. <br>
<br>
As she swings wildly and kicks, trying to buck out of his lap, he tightens his grasp on her and spanks her again. Getting a mouthfull of mud, she clamps her mouth down on his thigh and bites him hard. With a jump, he flings her off him to the edge of the muddy hole and she continues to roll down the side of the bank and splashes into the creek. He jumps up to follow her to see if she is alright, rubbing a hand on his thigh and sees her sitting up in the shallow creek. Not even noticing that the storm had subsided, the clouds have broken, and a beam of sunlight shines brightly down upon Saffryn's muddy head. <br>
<br>
Laughing heartily as he approaches the creek to give her a hand, he extends it to help her out, which of course, she takes and pulls him into the creek with her. They begin to splash and toss water at each other, eventually washing away all the mud until they are tired of the game and her anger has subsided. <br>
<br>
Gathering their things sitting cleanly against the gnarled old willow tree, they continue on to the lodge, Willowswood.<br>
<br>
&quot;I still don't believe you, ya know,&quot; she says as they enter the foyer of Willowswood. <br>
<br>
&quot;You don't have to, I suppose,&quot; he answers as he sees the look of dismay on Daina's face as she approaches, seeing the mess they are making on the floor.<br>
<br>
The housekeeper takes over, clucking and admonishing them like a couple of children and sends them upstairs to change into robes. <br>
<br>
They meet again, dryer and warmer and begin sipping brandy beside the fire in easy chairs, a small table between them, thinking quietly to themselves as they both fall asleep.<br>
