<br>
And now, the finale of Willowswood:<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
Crickets chirped under well-lit windows but were unheard by the Princes debating within the Hall. Five Princes of the Star Council and their Heirs stood alongside other Royals within the sidelines of the Court as unfamiliar faces weaved through the crowd as the King held the Court of the Full Moon. It was upon these sessions that subjects were allowed to bring cases before the King without going through the channels and red-tape of the lesser Royals. An argument had ensued over the astronomical taxation put upon the Feir'Dal Barons by the Koada'Dal Princes. Many Barons who normally would not attend this Court could be seen alongside faces of their Feir'Dal friends and workers who had never been this deep into Castle Felwithe.<br>
<br>
One Baron and One Prince stood toe to toe in heated debate upon the blue carpet engraved with fleur-de-lis that divided the King's hall down the middle from entry to throne. The King sat leaning upon one elbow, a finger to his brow. His wife sitting patiently beside him. He briefly thought back to the same arguments made in private council with his economists. They warned him that the Princes were out of control, driven with special influence of the Star Council. The Book of Tunare gave them special rights and guaranteed those rights as a &quot;parliament&quot; but they acted more as men who would tie the King's hands for their own gain and block the King at every move to right things between the Two Houses of the Eldritch. <br>
<br>
A single figure moved from the crowd, a woman. Feir'dal? Koada'Dal? She stood a height in-between and moved in a gown of green spiderling satin. Her warm-honey colored hair rippled in loose curls over bare shoulders. The boldness at her interuption stopped the argument and silenced the crowd as she approached the steps to the King's throne, daring to step up upon the first one uninvited.<br>
<br>
Cocking her head to the side, she asked quietly, &quot;My King, have you seen the Book of Tunare, with your own eyes? Do you judge the world on heresay, or do you know the truth with your own mind?&quot;<br>
<br>
Taken aback and thinking the girl a bit daft, he opened his mouth a bit and closed it as his wife and Queen put a soft hand upon her husband's own. &quot;I have sat quiet until this point, listening to arguments shifting like houses built upon sand,&quot; looking to the girl she continues, &quot;and what this young woman asks is a valid point. Should not an argument be made upon a more solid foundation?&quot;<br>
<br>
The arguing Prince interrupts, &quot;My Queen, the Book may be looked upon by only the Star Council,&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Nay, my Queen, for I have seen the book,&quot; the girl interrupts. Giving the Prince a look of death she continues, &quot;and do not say I have seen but a copy, for I have seen the original and bear the mark upon my wrist from where I was tested.&quot; She holds up her hand and her billowy sleeve falls back from her wrist to reveal a small mark. Turning to the King and Queen, she continues, &quot;The Princes of the Star Council know what made this mark, what device tested my blood, and I can tell you of this book, my Queen and King. I offer you my services, to take you to this Book that you may read it's truth with your own eyes.&quot;<br>
<br>
Bewilderment and confusion spreads among the court and Prince Joren steps from the crowd to join the arguers before the throne, &quot;Nay my King and Queen, this is a trick to take your very life. There are traps to the Book to ward off those who would destroy the book. They are set to take the life of any who is not of the Council. She would use these traps to harm you.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Who are you childe,&quot; the King asks, looking at the girl.<br>
<br>
&quot;I am Saffryn, born of Niola Impholder-Nobleheart and raised by the family of Trueheart.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Lies!&quot; hisses Prince Joren.<br>
<br>
&quot;Truth,&quot; says Wardrym as he steps from the crowd and joins Saffryn. &quot;This woman was born at Willowswood the night I was born in Kelethin to the family of Trueshot. The midwife, Miaza, switched us at birth to protect Niola Impholder from the wrath of Prince Joren should another of his heirs die in infancy. We stand before you, your Majesties, willing to be tested by clerics and proven that our stories are truth.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Together, Saffryn and I have worked to find the truth, in hopes to heal the widening between the Two Houses of Eldritch, the Feir'dal and Koada'Dal. We have seen the original Book that lies entombed in the Hidden-Tower, with traps to keep the truth hidden. Listen to us, please.&quot; Wardrym finishes.<br>
<br>
&quot;There is more, Majesties,&quot; Saffryn joins in. &quot;You need know that the five families that &quot;protect&quot; this book, the ones the wizard-locks answer to, are NOT the Star Council that was intended by Tunare. The locks were set to answer to those who would guard the book, long ago, and the task was handed down from heir to heir, but these are not the heirs to Tunare's Council. While the original intention may have been good, that five families protect the book, the ideal has been corrupted so long ago that no one remembers. The five that hold the book now, hold it in hostage, controlling everyone in the kingdom, even tying your own hands oft times, begging your pardon, my King. The Book of Tunare was wizard locked to answer to five families, but not to the true Star Council. Tunare meant the Eldritch to be led by both houses, Koada'Dal and Feir'Dal alike,&quot; Saffryn finishes.<br>
<br>
&quot;I should like to see this Book, the true and original Book of Tunare. We shall it it on the morrow. &quot; The King declares as he waves to his Chamberlain. Quickly all in attendance are vacated from the hall save for Saffryn, Wardrym, and the five Princes of the Star Council, sans their heirs.<br>
<br>
&quot;I swear to you, your majesty, this girl cannot be my daughter, this is all lies,&quot; he declares with a look of distain for Saffryn. &quot;Your life is at stake if you try to enter that chamber. The wizard lock is unforgiving and will only answer to the Star Council and our heirs. You must not go, your Highness. This is a trick to take your life.&quot; Joren pleads.<br>
<br>
&quot;Then you shall lead us in, Joren. If I die, you will be held responsible.&quot; the King responds.<br>
<br>
&quot;Wha…&quot; Joren begins to exclaim,<br>
<br>
&quot;You profess to know so much of the Book, you can prove yourself by disabling the locks yourself and I shall follow. If I die, you die. The Queen shall rule in my place,&quot; declares the King with a raised brow from his wife. &quot;Guards, take the council to their Hall to await the dawn. As for these two,&quot; he motions to Wardrym and Saffryn, &quot;Take them into seclusion and guard them well.&quot;<br>
<br>
<br>
